{
    "paragraphs": [
        {
            "text": "However, the author's favourite means for carrying such notions far back into the animal kingdom is the postulation of what he calls epideictic manifestations, instruments presumed to assess the population's own density and for becoming appropriately conditioned by it. The result of this conditioning is supposed to be control of the subsequent breeding output or dispersionary measures by emigration and the like.",
            "sentiment_score": 5,
            "mentions": [],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        },
        {
            "text": "Gatherings of the most diverse kinds are believed to have this function: communal nuptial displays, 'leks', aggregations for social roosting or hibernationeven the vertical migration of planktonic animals! The latter are thought to concentrate near the surface at fixed times of the day for 'epideictic' reasons.",
            "sentiment_score": 6,
            "mentions": [],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        },
        {
            "text": "It is difficult, to say the least, to see how this conditioning could come about and in what way it could influence the reproductive output. The bogong moth, to take an example, (p. 314), forms immense aestivating aggregations in clefts and caves of granite outcrops on selected mountain tops in the Australian Alps of New South Wales. What difference would it make for the single moth (even with so much milling around) whether there be one or two million moths present in a particular year, and how could this influence its subsequent reproductive output?",
            "sentiment_score": 3,
            "mentions": [],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        },
        {
            "text": "As a reason for believing that assemblages of this kind must have some special significance, the author maintains that, even if the finding of especially favoured sites for hibernation or roosting may thus be ensured, the gatherings may be harmful in making the population in question more vulnerable to predatory attack. Dr. ELLINOR BRO LARSEN has suggested to me an explanation involving exactly the opposite view. In her experience, even if a particular insect species is acceptable to a particular predator, protracted feeding experiments often show that the predator cannot eat more than a few individuals, it refuses to take more, and it may even show evidence of ill-effects. Thus, the prey-species in question appears to be mildly poisonous (e.g. various ladybirds and some collembola). In such cases the population may be better protected by being massed together, even if the animals are easier to find than in cases of individual hibernation or roosting.",
            "sentiment_score": 7,
            "mentions": [
                {
                    "text": "ELLINOR BRO LARSEN",
                    "sentiment_score": 6
                }
            ],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        },
        {
            "text": "In many cases gatherings (usually with displays) of animals certainly have a special social significance, but I think that the hitherto favoured explanation, viz. that they help to effect the partitioning of the species into more or less discrete populations, is the correct one (to have group-selection we must have groups). This problem will be treated in a special publication (BRAESTRUP 1963) , to which a criticism of W.-E.'s peculiar views concerning the role of the males in regulating fecundity will also be deferred.",
            "sentiment_score": 6,
            "mentions": [
                {
                    "text": "BRAESTRUP 1963",
                    "sentiment_score": 7
                },
                {
                    "text": "W.-E.",
                    "sentiment_score": 3
                }
            ],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        },
        {
            "text": "Just one more example of animal aggregations must be mentioned owing to a curious statement in the description of the swarming of whirligig beetles (Gyrinidae). It is said of them that 'their food is obtained entirely beneath the surface' (p. 77). This could give the impression that their interesting specializations for life at the water surface could be entirely for the sake of social integration. But in fact they take at least most of their food at the surface (see e.g. WESENBERG-LUND 1943. p. 317) .Perhaps there is confusion here with the behaviour of the larvae?",
            "sentiment_score": 5,
            "mentions": [
                {
                    "text": "Gyrinidae",
                    "sentiment_score": 5
                },
                {
                    "text": "WESENBERG-LUND 1943",
                    "sentiment_score": 6
                }
            ],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        },
        {
            "text": "We now come, finally, to that part of the book which, in my opinion, deserves the most violent opposition. I am alluding, of course, to the idea of an 'understanding' between competitors for the same resources. By interspecific conventions an auto-regulatory mechanism for two or several species together should be built up, similar to that existing within single species. This is sometimes believed to be so to the extent of presenting 'a radical antithesis to Gause's hypothesis that animals of similar ecology cannot survive together in the same habitat' (p. 18).",
            "sentiment_score": 2,
            "mentions": [
                {
                    "text": "Gause",
                    "sentiment_score": 3
                }
            ],
            "equation": null,
            "model": null,
            "author_view": true
        }
    ]
}

{
  "paragraphs": [
    {
      "text": "Of various closely related species which are difficult to tell apart by visual means (e.g. the species of Vespula) the author thinks that the resemblance may have been evolved, partly at least, for the sake of mutual integration. Among the examples mentioned we find, somewhat surprisingly, bees of the genus Halictus, of which there are many very similar species (some of them show beginnings of sociality, but this seems immaterial in the present connection). Sometimes very similar species nest together. It is apparently forgotten that in these bees an egg is never laid until food has been gathered for the larva in question, and furthermore the resources, honey and pollen, are not easily depleted, so here additional regulating mechanisms seem quite unnecessary.",
